After auctioning off 20  or so sketches this year for Sketchgiving,  I'm happy to report that thanks to YOU we raised $3404.14 to help 10 families in need over the holidays! All the families have sick kiddos and some are living in conditions close to poverty in Southern California. Thanks to you we were able to give each family $300 in gift cards so that they could buy groceries and possibly gifts for loved ones. We also got each family $50 gift cards for gas so that they can make to their doctor's appointments. I believe this is the 9th year of doing Sketchgiving and even though we've helped less families than in previous years we were able to give each family more as money doesn't go as far as it used to! 

I'd like to thank each and every single one of you who bid, won, and helped spread the word about Sketchgiving! I would especially like to thank Lester A R. and the Pay-It-Forward family for their super generous $500 donation. A big thank you also to all the artists who took the time from their day to draw and contribute sketches to help others. THANK YOU SO MUCH @ghost_etching , @cutthruyou , and @lisapenneyart !

 I witnessed a bit of holiday magic when a winner of a sketch requested the sketch be gifted to the person who had first bid on the sketch. It was already a wonderful gesture and then the the recipient matched and donated the amount that sketch raised- It was a wonderful surprise! 

It's amazing what we can do together. May your kindness be repaid to you in magical ways. The gift cards were sent to the families on December 17th. Thank you again and happy holidays everyone!❤️

“What do you mean all the characters don't have skin?" I had been pitching my Dia de los Muertos inspired children's book, SKELETOWN, to different publishers for over fifteen years! I got a lot of confused looks from publishers when I pitched them a book full of skeleton characters. Back then, the concept of Dia de los Muertos/ Day of the Dead was not in popular culture as it is today. These days you see Dia de los Muertos in all forms of popular media and they even sell Dia de los Muertos products at Target now. Thankfully, with publishers it went from countless "No, thank you's," to a four-book deal! The journey of bringing this series to reality has been a long road, but I feel grateful to have the opportunity to make a whole series. 

I am happy to announce the first SKELETOWN book, SI, ¡NO! which comes out August 1st and will be published by the fine folks at Little Brown. I'm excited to finally be able to talk about the series and share a peek of the first cover with everyone. SI, ¡NO! is a humor picture book that features Skully and Skelly. The book has only two words in it with a story that is for EVERYONE, not just Spanish speakers.

Pre-orders help immensely with the life of a book. If you are interested and if you can, please pre-order the first SKELETOWN book.

I can’t believe the big day is here! Today the first book of my SKELETOWN series Si, No, is out and I’m so excited! It has been a long road getting here so today feels exceptionally surreal! I first drew some of the SKELETOWN characters back in 2004 and started pitching the concept of SKELETOWN to publishers in 2008. It was inspired by the Mexican holiday Dia de los Muertos. Inspiration also comes from Charles Schulz’s PEANUTS and the classic Mexican TV show, EL CHAVO DEL OCHO, by Roberto Gómez Bolaños “Chespirito”. It’s wild to think that this journey of bringing SKELETOWN to the public started almost 20 years ago! Back then editors and publishers were not familiar with Dia de los Muertos as they are today, but I kept trying and trying, and I then finally got a 4-book series deal thanks to the good folks at Little, Brown and Company. I challenged myself with the first book to have only two Spanish words in hopes that the visuals could lead the story as well as show the concept of Si, No. My hope is that the book is universal to every kid, adult and non-Spanish speaker. The books are truly made for everyone!

Thank you to everyone who supported SKELETOWN from the beginning and picked up my zine, prints, shirts, etc. at conventions long ago when I was trying to do it on my own (you’ll know you have the original SKELETOWN if it has the color pink in it, I’ve since updated it with neon orange!) I appreciate every one of you who pre-ordered the book! You should start getting it in the mail today or real soon! If you like the book, I encourage you to write an online review- it really helps!

Thank you to my EMLA literary agent Kevin Lewis who helped me with his wisdom and encouragement of finding the right home for the series. Thank you to my excellent editor, Andrea Spooner, and the awesome design team at Little Brown who helped elevate the book! Thank you to Esther Cajahuaringa who first saw the potential of a SKELETOWN picture book series and to Reka Simonsen who planted the seed about possibly doing a book with only 2 words! Thanks to Jamie Baker who helped come up with the SKELETOWN title name and Kenn Navarro for this animation! ¡Bienvenidos a SKELETOWN! -Rhode

This year due to a family emergency I wasn’t able to do as many Sketchgiving sketches as I would have hoped. The annual Sketchgiving helps raise money to help families in need  that have kiddos with ​chronic medical conditions. Since I wasn’t able to produce as many sketches this year, I thought I would be able to help one or two families, but then a wonderful thing happened- a few of you stepped in to help and together we were able to raise enough to help 10 families in need! The helping happened in different ways, some artists contributed sketches and others bid on sketches and contributed a little bit more than the winning amount and some people simply donated! And it all added up! $3500 were raised thanks to you!

Thank you to these generous artists that helped with their art: @ghost_etching , @ague_designs , @kirdybirds, @zanshin_923 and thank you to these generous folks for their personal donations @ghost_etching, John B., Kevin P., Andrea H. and a special shout out to Lester A.R. @bats69 and his Pay It Forward Family who donated $1,225.00 which was an enormous boost in helping raise enough this year! THANK YOU SO MUCH! 

Lester and his group also inspired me to give one more push on the last day of Sketchgiving and I held a live sketch-a-thon/auction which was fun and helpful!  Thank you to all who bid and those who helped spread the word about Sketchgiving! Please  forgive me if I forgot to thank other individuals that helped this year.

On the next photo you will see we tried something different this year and got each family $350 dollars each in money orders to be able to buy groceries, gifts, and necessities-these were sent out on December 14. 

It is a gift to be reminded of the generosity and willingness from all of you coming together to help. I have tremendous gratitude to you all and I know that each family was helped and touched by your support and generosity. Happy holidays to you and yours! -Rhode
